"'''Better Be Good to Me'''" is a hit [[Single (music)|single]] from [[Tina Turner]]'s solo [[album]], ''[[Private Dancer]]''. The song had originally been released in 1981 by [[Spider (band)|Spider]], a band from [[New York City]] with co-writer [[Holly Knight]] as a member. The Turner version was successful in the [[United States]] on the Hot 100 and the [[R&B/Hip-Hop Tracks chart|US R&B/Hip-Hop]] chart. It peaked at number five on the [[Billboard Hot 100]] and number six on the US R&B/Hip-hop chart. At the 1985 [[Grammy Awards]] ceremony, Turner won the Grammy for [[Grammy Award for Best Female Rock Vocal Performance|Best Female Rock Vocal Performance]] for this song.

==Music video==
In the [[Music video|video]] Tina Turner is seen performing this song on stage. She is wearing a black leather jacket, and black skin tight knee length leather pants, with leopard print high heels and spikey blond hair. Towards the end of the song a man appears on stage ([[Cy Curnin]] of [[The Fixx]]), grabs Tina's arms and Tina looks him in the eyes and sings the words "Why can't you be good to me?" to him and then pushes the man away. At the end of the video Tina disappears under the stage in a puff of smoke. Both Curnin and the guitarist in the video, Jamie West-Oram (also of [[The Fixx]]), perform on the ''[[Private Dancer]]'' album.

==Versions and remixes==
* 7" Edit - 3:39
* Album Version - 5:10
* Extended 12" Remix - 7:47

